text.tspan: Figure a2. Wicklefeature dictionary least squares solution, N=1000. The algorithm calculates the
closed form least squares solution to present tense verbs (X), and corresponding past tense verbs
(Y) for a set training set size. We can see perfect similarity with the training set up until
1000 words, equivalent to N. Its lower test similarities imply that the algorithm is biased towards
higher similarities by having the solution update via addition.
Figure a3. Wickelfeature difference dictionary least squares solution, N=10000. We can see
perfect similarity with the training set up until 1000 words, equivalent to N. In this case, its
test similarities are close enough to those of the difference algorithm to determine that updating
the model by addition does not significantly bias similarities.
Figure a4. Wickelfeature dictionary, N=1000. The model (W) is an N by N matrix. We can see
more explicitly how the algorithm's binding rule is related to least squares because of how
the least squares solution uses an inverse as a regularization rule and the same binding (XY).
Figure a5. Wickelfeature dictionary, N=10000. The model (W) is an N by N matrix. We include
the algorithm's regularization rule in constructing W.
Figure a6. Wickelfeature difference dictionary with regularization, N=1000. The model (W) is an
N by N matrix. The difference algorithm reflects the difference least squares solution in how W
is not bound by XY, but instead by X1 (Y2 - X2). It does not include the least squares solution's
inverse for regularization.
Figure a7. Wickelfeature difference dictionary with regularization, N=10000. We include the
difference algorithm's regularization rule in constructing W.
